The precise nature of the pommhm is disputed but it may be taken in a general way to mean the boundary lineos a town or seulement, the ground within which was consecrated and so marked off from the surrounding ager. It originated‚ according to Varro Lingua Latina v. 143, in the old Etmscan habitos drawing a line round anew settlement with a plough and a yoke of oxen3 the trench cut by the plough was called the fossa and the lineos earth thrown up on the inner side the murus, then the line or strip of ground behind, ie. inside (according to some, outside) the wall was called the pos-merium or ponarium (cp. pomeridzbnus); sometimes the word denoted the whole os the interior space, so that pomerium and urbs were almost equivalent. As the state grew the pomerium had to be moved farther outwards, and this was done by Sulla and by Caesar.
